{"id":"1904.06977","submitter":"Stefan Landmann","authors":"Stefan Landmann and Andreas Engel","title":"On non-negative solutions to large systems of random linear equations","comments":"10 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.physa.2019.122544","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.stat-mech q-bio.PE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Systems of random linear equations may or may not have solutions with all\ncomponents being non-negative. The question is, e.g., of relevance when the\nunknowns are concentrations or population sizes. In the present paper we show\nthat if such systems are large the transition between these two possibilities\noccurs at a sharp value of the ratio between the number of unknowns and the\nnumber of equations. We analytically determine this threshold as a function of\nthe statistical properties of the random parameters and show its agreement with\nnumerical simulations. We also make contact with two special cases that have\nbeen studied before: the storage problem of a perceptron and the resource\ncompetition model of MacArthur.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Apr 2019 11:54:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-06-24"}
